2. Suppose society decided to reduce consumption and increase investment:
   a. How would this change affect economic growth?
   b. What groups in society would benefit from this change? What groups might be hurt?

3. Societies choose what share of resources to devote to consumption and what share to investment. Some decisions involve private spending; others involve government spending:
   a. Describe some forms of private spending that represent consumption and some that represent investment. National income accounts include tuition as part of consumer spending. In your opinion, are resources you devote to education a form of consumption or investment?
   b. Describe some forms of government spending that represent consumption and some that represent investment. In your opinion, should we view government spending on health care for elderly as form of consumption or investment? Would you distinguish between health programs for young and health programs for elderly?

4. What is opportunity cost of investing in capital? What is opportunity cost of investing in human capital? Do you think country can overinvest in capital? In human capital? Explain.

5. In 1990s and first decade of 2000s, investors from Asian economies of Japan and China made significant direct and portfolio investments in United States. At time, many Americans were unhappy that this investment was occurring:
   a. In what way was it better for United States to receive this foreign investment than not to receive it?
   b. In what way would it have been better still for Americans to have made this investment?

6. In many developing nations, young women have lower enrollment rates in secondary school than young men. Describe several ways in which greater educational opportunities for young women could lead to faster economic growth in these countries.

